metadata.name: HERE & NOW PORTALS #326
metadata.description:
The 'Portal' is your gateway to 'The Passage' created by HERE & NOW. This interactive minting project seeks to transform the traditional minting experience into something truly unique and unexpected.

Each 'Portal' gives you access and 1x reserve for all future 'The Passage' experiences both virtual and IRL.

For more information, visit hereandnow.events or join the discord, and join us in redefining what it means to mint.

See LICENCE.md for license details.

TECHNOLOGY :::::::::

This token is designed using a custom-built raymarching engine, built in a way that allows me to pass in chunks of GLSL code as determined by the params and features.

The geometry is generated using what's called a KIFS (Kaleidoscopic Iterated Function System) fractal, which involves taking the space, folding it, offsetting it, drawing in it, and repeating. By doing this, we can create some *very* complex appearing geometry using some relatively simple rules.

Finally, this is an intense simulation and requires a somewhat powerful GPU to properly be enjoyed.

CONTROLS :::::::::::

Mouse - Click and drag to move the camera around in the space.
Q/E - Roll the camera.
R/F - Change the speed of the camera.
SPACE - Stop the camera from moving.
O - Output a still picture without DOF.
P - Output a still picture with DOF.

URL PARAMS :::::::::

&still=true
This will just render a still image.

&dpr=X
Where X is a number. Will allow you to render the token to a higher or lower resolution

&fullscreen=true
Allows you to render the token at the screen resolution of your browser.

&width=X &height=Y
Allows you to set the specific dimensions of the token.

&dof=true
Turns fake depth of field on.

&doflenngth=X
Changes the length at with the DOF is calculated.

&steps=X
Allows you to explicitly set the number of steps the raymarcher can use.

metadata.name: aRo #224
metadata.description:
aRo "a Representation of"

Like a ladder or a hammer, art is often a tool. The less practical and most bizarre, basically the most overcomplicated self-made tool anyone could ever imagine. But it's THE tool to explore ideas.
I created this one to investigate, to poke and nudge at a few concepts that seem to go hand-in-hand.
Firstly, Representation, as in changing something to better explain it. Metaphors, symbols, codes —the very fabric of art, religion, and society. And secondly, the aesthetics of recursion or accumulation.

While many generative art projects pick buildings and landscapes as their subject, most artworks are made of particles arranged, connected and stretched to create bigger structures, to become textures or both.

But there's a distinct texture that arises from mobs. And another, somewhat similar, that belongs to the accumulation and hoarding of not-same-objects or shapes.

I can't tell if it's a street grid, a collage, a group of shrines or actual cells, but to scratch all these potential meanings using accumulation, hoarding and mobs, is what brought the texture I was looking for.

What happens when a flower has more petals than pixels? Why do we know there's more layers to that thumbnail?
My best answer is:

metadata.name: Lianas #16
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by op'art and physics simulation. A perfect structure is created at first and gets destructed by repulsing forces making the whole edifice deform itself.

Thechnically this work is a grid of nodes that repel each other. Each node on each row is connected to its neighboor with a digital spring maintaining the equilibrium.

A random number of repulsing nodes are placed randomely on each generation, making the lines move from their initial alignment.

Final image is generated in about 500 frames as nodes stop to move.

metadata.name: The Wintertime #105
metadata.description:
"The Wintertime" is a collection of generative art that captures the essence of the winter season in a glitchy and abstract way. The pieces in this collection are a visual representation of the harshness and beauty of winter, where the cold and barren landscapes are juxtaposed against the sparkling snow and ice. The glitches and digital distortions in the art add a sense of chaos and unpredictability, mirroring the unpredictable nature of winter weather. The collection celebrates the winter season in all its raw and untamed glory. Each piece is unique and evocative, inviting the viewer to get lost in the beauty of the wintertime.

The work was inspired by the drip painting technique of Jackson Pollock and the minimalistic elegance of Japanese prints. Combining these two distinct styles creates a visually striking and thought-provoking collection that pays homage to the masters while pushing the boundaries of contemporary art.

This collection is the continuation of GPTree: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/17691

Genuary 2023: Recursive trees
